[medium] src/views/__tests__/DiagnosticsRouting.spec.ts:11 (test quality)
The new routing spec imports the app singleton router, drives createWebHistory with router.push(), and waits on router.isReady(). It passes in isolation, but the documented full command npm run test:unit fails: this test times out after 5000 ms with jsdom reporting navigation is not implemented, so the suite is now order/global-history dependent.
Suggested fix: Avoid driving the singleton createWebHistory router in this spec. Assert the redirect record via router.getRoutes(), or create an isolated memory-history router for the test and reset modules/state between cases so npm run test:unit is deterministic.
Guidance: In src/views/__tests__/DiagnosticsRouting.spec.ts, stop importing the singleton router from @/router and stop calling router.push()/router.isReady() against createWebHistory in jsdom. The test only needs to verify the compatibility redirect, so assert route configuration instead: import the router, call router.getRoutes(), find the route whose path is /admin/notifications or name is admin-notifications, and expect its redirect to equal { name: 'admin-diagnostics-notifications' }. If you want to test real navigation, create a local createRouter with createMemoryHistory and the relevant route records inside the spec, but do not drive the app singleton. Keep the Pinia/auth setup only if the chosen approach actually exercises guards; otherwise remove it to avoid global state coupling.
